Gotta cherish all the one on one time before adding another to the mix!
What’s funny is over the weekend I got so many DMs: “You’re such a good dad. You dressed her?! You did her hair? You took the kids by yourself?” You get the gist. 
Although I appreciate all of your kind words, I feel like there is such a double standard or lack of a standard for dads. 
If Emily (or any other mom) went and did the exact same things I did, she would get no praise. Just because “that’s what moms are supposed to do”…
So to all the moms who never get told you’re doing a good job - you’re doing great! 
To the dads who don’t do these things with their kids…all I can say is you’re missing out! 
And to all the actively involved parents out there - keep crushing it 👊 you’re building a foundation and memories they’ll never forget.

Paris photo dump 🥐 

#EmilyInParis 

📷: @michaeljasonlloyd 
  @dylanfauver 😜

Take me back to Paris 🥖🥂
Yes we did more than take pics around the Eiffel Tower and drink wine and champagne 😂 But when in Paris…it’s just something you’ve got to do. 
It was such an amazing trip and I’d definitely go back. For one, it’s beautiful there. The architecture is unreal and the history that goes with it is pretty cool too. The Louvre, the museums, Norte Dame and even just the random pieces around the city were all great sights to see. 
Two, the pace of life is just so much different than the US. Things are just more relaxed there and nobody is rushing you along. A typical dinner is nearly 3 hours there! We’d be kicked out in a hurry for the next customer if we tried that here in the US. 
Three, everyone is so active and the food is much more fresh. We could learn a thing or two for sure. 
And most importantly everyone we met seemed genuinely happy! 
There’s so much more but just thought I’d share that if you’re ever thinking about taking a trip to Paris - go for it! 

If you’ve ever been. What’d you think?

Not the #32WeeksPregnant bumpdate I wanted to share, but if you haven’t been watching my stories you might have missed what’s been going on in our world the past few days. 

Starting on Tuesday I was feeling less movement but just assumed we were having an off day. Wednesday rolled around and even less movement. He normally wakes me up with wiggles, responds to the food I eat, Ella’s voice, etc and I wasn’t getting anything from him. In fact, as soon as he didn’t move when Ella talked to him that’s when I knew something was wrong. 

Long story short, I went to L&D on Wednesday at 6pm to be monitored. It didn’t take long to realize there was an issue and his heart rate kept dropping drastically with every contraction or big move. They would call in the team and do everything to get it back. There was a handful of times that night I thought we were losing him.

Next day I was transferred by helicopter to a bigger city hospital with a nicu. We’ve been here since have have since found out baby boy has his chord wrapped around his neck twice and is head down. So with every contraction and big move, it’s tightening his chord and causing his HR to drop. 

We will be here until further notice with 24/7 monitoring just waiting for his lungs to become more developed due to the steroid shots I’ve been given.

Good news is, he’s “a big boy” lol Ella’s been right all along. He’s already 5 pounds and there is nothing physically wrong with him. We are just praying he can stay put a little longer and keep his heartrate up, but we are still experiencing consistent dips. 

I see your messages, and I wish I could respond to every single one. But we’ve never have felt so loved and surrounded in prayer and appreciate it more than you know.
We love you guys.

The best medicine right here!
It looks like we’re going to be in the hospital for a while but we’re in great hands and right where we need to be. So thankful for family, friends, all the selfless medical staff and the support all of you have shown us.
We’ll see you soon son - just hopefully not too soon 🙏

My little man is 2 month old today!

The question I get asked all the time is “what are you most excited about to have a son?”

And I never answer it because honestly, I don’t know. I thought I’d say to play catch with him, or ride bikes, or wrestle or do all of things that I used to do with my dad when I was a kid. And don’t get me wrong, I loved doing all of those things. I had (still have) a very active involved dad who did everything with me and coached about every team I was on. But here’s the thing…just because I loved doing those activities with my dad, Nash may not, and that’s totally fine. 

So to answer the question. I’m most excited to watch him grow up to be a man who is passionate about what he does, whatever that may be. I’m excited to be the supportive father who helps him achieve his dreams, whatever they may be. I’ll let him live and learn and find out what HE wants to do, not me, and THAT thing, THAT is what I’m most excited about. 

I’m excited to teach him that no matter what he does, he has to give it his all and that success doesn’t just happen without effort. I’m excited to watch and help my son become a well respected, hard working, loyal, and kind gentleman! 

But for now…I’m just going to work on cherishing every moment that I can still hold him in my arms. 

Happy 2 month son! Love you!

- Dad
